ty. The contributors emphasize the complex interaction of state and society during this tumultuous period, exploring the way events originating at the center of political power changed people's lives and how, in turn, people's responses took the Cultural Revolution in unplanned and unanticipated directions. This approach offers a more fruitful way to understand the Cultural Revolution and its historical legacies. The book provides a new look at the student Red Guard movements, the effort to identify and cultivate potential “revolutionary” leaders in outlying provinces, stubborn resistance to campaigns to destroy the old culture, and the violence and mass killings in rural China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aAnthropology - Asia. 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory -- Asian. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsherick, Joseph W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsherick, Joseph W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHe, Jiangsui, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHo, Dahpon David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPickowicz, Paul G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPickowicz, Paul G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aQin, Liyan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmalzer, Sigrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSu, Yang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalder, Andrew G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalder, Andrew G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZhang, Elya J., econt